  "chunk_index": 43,
  "summary": "Arthur Calgary confronts Kirsten Lindström regarding the murder of Mrs. Aigle. While Calgary had previously provided an alibi for Jack Aigle, he now posits that Jack was the mastermind who manipulated Kirsten into committing the murder. Calgary explains that Jack exploited Kirsten's affection for him to convince her to kill Mrs. Aigle between seven and seven-thirty to facilitate a theft. Kirsten breaks down, admitting her love for Jack but claiming his actions were evil rather than her own.\n\nCalgary further accuses Kirsten of murdering Philip Darwent and stabbing Tina. He reveals that Tina’s cryptic phrase, \"the cup is empty,\" indicated that Kirsten had stabbed Philip while pretending to bring him coffee, leaving an empty cup on the floor. Kirsten admits to these killings, driven by fear and a desire to protect herself after realizing that Jack had deceived her. Following this revelation, Mary Darland attacks Kirsten in a rage before leaving the room in grief.\n\nAs the group processes the truth, Leo Aigle defends Kirsten's character, suggesting her actions stemmed from suffering, while Gwendolyn Vaughan remains resentful of the torment Kirsten caused. Calgary suggests that Kirsten will likely flee to London but will eventually be caught. The discussion turns to Tina’s recovery and her relationship with Mickey. In a moment of shifting emotions, Hester expresses a sudden desire to marry Calgary.",
